{"title_page": "Champlain Bridge, Montreal (2019\u2013present)", "text_new": "{{short description|Bridge over the Saint Lawrence River in Montreal, Quebec}}\n{{About|the newly constructed bridge spanning the Saint Lawrence River|the old bridge it replaced|Champlain Bridge, Montreal (1962\u20132019)}}\n{{others|Champlain Bridge (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| bridge_name      = Samuel De Champlain Bridge\n| native_name      = {{native name|fr|Pont Samuel-De Champlain}}\n| image            = File:Samuel de Champlain Bridge from east.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Samuel De Champlain Bridge as viewed from Brossard\n| official_name    = \n| other_name       = \n| carries          = 8 lanes (4 northwestbound, 4 southeastbound) of {{jct|province=QC|A|10|A|15|A|20}}\n| crosses          = [[St. Lawrence River]] and [[Saint Lawrence Seaway]]\n| locale           = [[Brossard]] and [[Montreal]], Quebec, Canada\n| owner            = The Jacques Cartier and Champlain Bridges Inc.\n| maint            = The Jacques Cartier and Champlain Bridges Inc.\n| id               = \n| website          = https://www.newchamplain.ca/\n| architect        = [[Poul Ove Jensen]]\n| designer         = [[T.Y. Lin International]]\n| engineering      = \n| winner           = \n| design           = [[Cable-stayed bridge]]\n| material         = [[Steel]], [[Concrete]]\n| length           = {{convert|3400|m|ft|sigfig=5|abbr=on}}\n| width            = {{convert|60|m|ft|sigfig=5|abbr=on}}\n| height           = {{convert|170|m|ft|sigfig=5|abbr=on}}\n| mainspan         = \n| spans            = \n| lanes            = \n| pierswater       = \n| load             = \n| clearance        = \n| below            = \n| life             = 125 years\n| builder          = [[SNC-Lavalin]], [[ACS Group]], Dragados Canada\n| fabricator       = \n| begin            = 2015\n| complete         = 2019\n| cost             = $4.2 billion<ref name=\"bruemmer\">{{cite web |last1=Bruemmer |first1=Rene |title=New Champlain Bridge set to open by the end of June |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/new-champlain-bridge-set-to-open-june-3 |website=Montreal Gazette |accessdate=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n| open             = {{Start date|2019|06|24}} (northbound/westbound span)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Magner |first1=Jason |title=Drivers line up to be first across new Champlain Bridge |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/drivers-line-up-to-be-the-first-across-new-champlain-bridge |accessdate=July 7, 2019 |agency=Montreal Gazette |publisher=Postmedia Network Inc. |date=June 24, 2019}}</ref><br>{{Start date|2019|07|1}} (southbound/eastbound span)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scott |first1=Marian |title=Farewell to old Champlain Bridge as new one opens to southbound traffic |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/end-of-the-road-for-champlain-bridge |accessdate=July 7, 2019 |agency=Montreal Gazette |publisher=Postmedia Network, Inc. |date=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n| closed =\n| inaugurated      = {{Start date|2019|06|28}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Magner |first1=Jason |title=Champlain Bridge inaugurated, but much work still left to do |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/champlain-bridge-inaugurated-but-much-work-still-left-to-do |accessdate=July 7, 2019 |agency=Montreal Gazette |publisher=Postmedia Network Inc. |date=June 28, 2019}}</ref>\n| replaces = [[Champlain Bridge, Montreal (1962\u20132019)]]\n| toll             = \n| traffic          = 159,000\n| coordinates = {{Coord|45|28|10|N|73|30|58|W|region:CA_scale:landmark_scale:50000|display=inline,title}}\n| mapframe_zoom    = 12\n| mapframe_caption = {{Location map|Canada Montreal\n |border  = infobox\n |float   = center\n |lon_dir = W\n |lat_dir = N\n |lat_deg = 45\n |lat_min = 28\n |lat_sec = 10\n |lon_deg = 73\n |lon_min = 30\n |lon_sec = 58\n |width   = 250\n |caption = Location on a map of Montreal\n }}\n}}\n\nThe '''Samuel De Champlain Bridge''' is a twin [[cable-stayed bridge]] built to replace the [[Champlain Bridge, Montreal (1962\u20132019)|original Champlain Bridge]] over the [[Saint Lawrence River]] in [[Quebec]] between the [[Island of Montreal]] and the [[South Shore (Montreal)|South Shore]] suburbs. The new twin spans are located just north of the original Champlain Bridge, which both run east-west over the north-south river. The new bridge's north span carries the northbound and westbound automobile traffic of the [[Quebec Autoroute 10|A-10]], [[Quebec Autoroute 15|A-15]], and [[Quebec Autoroute 20|A-20]]. The south span carries the southbound and eastbound automobile traffic of the A-10, A-15 and A-20. The central span, still under construction, will carry the South Shore branch of the forthcoming [[R\u00e9seau express m\u00e9tropolitain]] (REM) automated light rail system. It is one of the largest [[infrastructure]] projects in [[North America]] and is one of the busiest crossings on the continent.<ref name=\"olson\">{{cite web |last1=Olson |first1=Isaac |title=It comes with sacrifices': After 4-year slog, Samuel De Champlain Bridge a source of pride for workers |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/samuel-de-champlain-bridge-workers-sacrifices-1.5192452 |website=CBC |accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref> It is built to last 125 years with the usage of [[stainless steel]] and [[high-performance concrete]],<ref>{{cite web |title=New Samuel De Champlain Bridge built for performance, not style, says architect |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/new-samuel-de-champlain-bridge-1.5194035 |website=CBC |accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref> and replaces the previous [[Champlain Bridge, Montreal (1962\u20132019)|57-year-old bridge]],<ref name=philippe>{{cite web |last1=Teisceira-Lessard |first1=Philippe |title=Pont Champlain: un d\u00e9lai \"tr\u00e8s court\", dit l'architecte |url=https://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/grand-montreal/201312/06/01-4718225-pont-champlain-un-delai-tres-court-dit-larchitecte.php |website=La Presse |accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref> which has become functionally obsolete and its structure having been degraded by the repeated application of de-icing salt. At approximately {{convert|60|m|ft|adj=off}} wide, the new Champlain Bridge is one of the widest bridges in the world.\n\nThe bridge includes lanes for light rail, cyclists, and pedestrians, and four lanes in each direction for road traffic, with one in each direction being reserved for busses.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lau |first1=Rachel |title=Montreal\u2019s new Samuel de Champlain Bridge opens northbound |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5424374/montreals-new-samuel-de-champlain-bridge-opens-northbound/ |website=Global News |accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, the federal government selected the JV consortium: Signature on the St. Lawrence Group to build the new bridge. The consortium mainly includes: [[SNC-Lavalin]], ACS Infrastructure, and Dragados Canada. [[T.Y. Lin International]] is serving as the Lead Designer.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Champlain Bridge Corridor Project|url=http://www.roadtraffic-technology.com/projects/new-champlain-bridge-corridor-project/|website=Road-Traffic Technology.com|accessdate=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Specifications==\nIt is an asymmetric cable-stayed bridge with a {{convert|168|m|ft|adj=mid|-high}} concrete tower and stay cables in a harp arrangement. It will include a two-lane rail corridor for the [[R\u00e9seau express m\u00e9tropolitain]], a six-lane corridor for vehicles, and a multi-use corridor for cyclists and pedestrians. Components of the $4{{nbsp}}billion project include:\n* The Samuel-de-Champlain Bridge<ref>{{cite web|title=New Champlain Bridge Project Website|url=http://www.newchamplain.ca/project/engineering/|website=newchamplain.ca|accessdate=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n* A new [[Quebec Autoroute 10|Autoroute 10]] (A-10) approach\n* A new {{convert|470|m|ft|adj=mid}} [[Nuns' Island|\u00eele-des-S\u0153urs]] bridge and a highway on \u00eele-des-Soeurs\n* Improvements to nearby parts of the [[Quebec Autoroute 15|A-15]]\n\n==Construction history==\nIn September 2007, faced with rising costs for the maintenance of the Champlain Bridge (commissioned in 1962), then Canadian [[Minister of Transport (Canada)|Minister of Transport]] [[Lawrence Cannon]] confirmed that his department was seriously considering the construction of a replacement structure. In August 2008, [[Transport Canada]] announced that it was exploring different scenarios for a new bridge. In October 2011, then Minister of Transport [[Denis Lebel]] officially announced that construction on the new bridge would begin within 10 years.\n\nIn November 2014, then Minister of Transport [[Lisa Raitt]] announced that she was abandoning the idea of naming the new bridge in honour of [[Maurice Richard]] after consulting the family of the former ice hockey champion. Prior to the [[2015 Canadian federal election]], the [[28th Canadian Ministry]] planned on imposing a $2-$4 toll on the new bridge, however, this plan was abandoned following the election of the [[29th Canadian Ministry]].\n\nConstruction on the new bridge officially began on June 16, 2015. On December 19, 2018, [[Minister of Infrastructure and Communities]] [[Fran\u00e7ois-Philippe Champagne]] announced that the official name of the new bridge will be the Samuel-de-Champlain Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Magder |first1=Jason |title=The new Champlain Bridge is finished \u2014 mostly |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/the-new-champlain-bridge-is-finished-mostly |accessdate=July 7, 2019 |agency=Montreal Gazette |publisher=Postmedia Network Inc. |date=December 19, 2019}}</ref> The bridge opened to northbound/westbound traffic on June 24, 2019 ([[St-Jean-Baptiste Day]]), with the official opening ceremony being held on June 28, 2019, and southbound/eastbound traffic opening on July 1, 2019 ([[Canada Day]]). The multi-purpose runway is scheduled to open in the fall of 2019, while the REM train tracks are expected to be opened in 2021.\n\n==Construction method==\n[[File:New Champlain Bridge Montreal.jpg|thumb|left|View from the westbound roadway]]\nIn order to meet the 42-month construction deadline, many steel and concrete bridge elements were prefabricated, with a portion of the work taking place on temporary piers. Three jetties were built: one on the east from Brossard, one on the west from Nuns' Island, and one from the center, adjacent to a dike along the [[Saint Lawrence Seaway]].\n*The pier through the canal, allowed, by means of [[cofferdam]]s, the storage of piles of construction material.\n*The central jetty served as a construction platform for the piers and towers of the section of the bridge utilizing [[guy-wire]]s. Temporary pillars used during the construction of the [[Millau Viaduct]] in [[France]] were erected to support the cable-stayed span during construction. The main cable-stayed span above the seaway was assembled in segments by means of a crane.\n*The 500-meter (550 yard) long west pier was divided into three pre-assembly areas: a first for the concrete foundation footings that serve as the base for the viaduct section crossing the river, a second for the steel headers that complete the piles, and a third for the steel superstructures that wear the aprons. During the prefabrication of the 38 marine insoles, a pile primer and working platform were added to form a pile base measuring up to 14 meters (45') high. A super-transporter moved these stack bases from the prefabrication area to a loading area from where they were lifted by an industrial catamaran. The catamaran then deposited these bases in spaces drilled to a depth of 4 to 5 meters (15') in the riverbed. Two floating cranes finally overlaid the bases of the prefabricated elements to form piles and headers. The steel box girders supporting the three decks of the bridge were then deposited on the trimmers as they were completed.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of crossings of the Saint Lawrence River#Quebec|List of crossings of the Saint Lawrence River]]\n* [[List of bridges in Montreal]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline|Samuel-De Champlain Bridge}}\n\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure        = Bridges\n|place            = [[St. Lawrence River]]\n|bridge           = Samuel-de-Champlain Bridge\n|bridge signs     = [[File:Quebec Autoroute 10.svg|25px]] [[File:Quebec Autoroute 15.svg|25px]] [[File:Quebec Autoroute 20.svg|25px]]\n|upstream         = [[Honor\u00e9 Mercier Bridge]]\n|upstream signs   = [[Image:qc138.svg|25px]]\n|downstream       = [[Victoria Bridge (Montreal)|Victoria Bridge]]\n|downstream signs = [[Image:qc112.svg|25px]]\n}}\n\n{{Streets in Montreal}}\n\n{{Urban agglomeration of Longueuil}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Champlain Bridge, Montreal (2019-present)}}\n[[Category:Cable-stayed bridges]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 2019]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Transport in Brossard]]\n[[Category:Bridges over the Saint Lawrence River]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Brossard]]\n[[Category:Verdun, Quebec]]\n[[Category:Le Sud-Ouest]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Quebec]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bridge over the Saint Lawrence River in Montreal, Quebec}}\n{{About|the newly constructed bridge spanning the Saint Lawrence River|the old bridge it replaced|Champlain Bridge, Montreal (1962\u20132019)}}\n{{others|Champlain Bridge (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n| bridge_name      = Samuel De Champlain Bridge\n| native_name      = {{native name|fr|Pont Samuel-De Champlain}}\n| image            = File:Samuel de Champlain Bridge from east.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Samuel De Champlain Bridge as viewed from Brossard\n| official_name    = \n| other_name       = \n| carries          = 8 lanes (4 northwestbound, 4 southeastbound) of {{jct|provin