ities]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with precognition]]\n[[Category:Fictional dictators]]\n[[Category:Fictional warlords]]\n[[Category:Fictional filicides]]\n[[Category:Fictional patricides]]\n[[Category:Fictional matricides]]\n[[Category:Fictional fratricides]]\n[[Category:Fictional sororicides]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who committed genocide]]\n[[Category:Fictional gentry]]\n[[Category:Fictional lords and ladies]]\n[[Category:Fictional senators]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional mass murderers]]\n[[Category:Fictional spymasters]]\n[[Category:Fictional telekinetics]]\n[[Category:Galactic emperors]]\n[[Category:Male film villains]]\n[[Category:Male characters in film]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n[[Category:Star Wars comics characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars literary characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars Skywalker Saga characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars television characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars video game characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars Sith characters]]\n[[Category:Video game bosses]]\n", "name_user": "73.9.249.206", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palpatine"}
{"title_page": "HAT-P-32b", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox planet\n| name                     = HAT-P-32b\n<!-- DISCOVERY           -->\n| discoverer               = Hartman ''et al.''<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n| discovery_site           = [[HATNet]] ([[Fred Lawrence Whipple Observatory|FLWO]])/[[W.M. Keck Observatory|Keck]]<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n| discovered               = Published 3 November 2011<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n| discovery_method         = [[Transit method]]<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n<!-- ORBITAL             --> \n| epoch                    = J2000\n| apsis                    = astron\n| semimajor                = {{Val|0.0343|0.0004|ul=AU}}<ref name=EPE />\n| eccentricity             = {{Val|0.0072|0.07|0.0064}}<ref name=EPE />\n| period                   = {{Val|2.1500103|0.0000003|ul=d}}<ref name=\"Sada2012\"/>\n| inclination              = {{Val|88.9|0.4|ul=\u00b0}}<ref name=EPE />\n| arg_peri                 = {{Val|96|180|11}}<ref name=EPE />\n| star                     = [[HAT-P-32]] (GSC 3281-00800)\n<!-- PHYS CHARS          --> \n| mean_radius              = {{Val|1.789|0.025|u={{Jupiter radius|link=y}}}}<ref name=EPE />\n| mass                     = {{Val|0.86|0.164|u={{Jupiter mass|link=y}}}}<ref name=EPE />\n| surface_grav             = {{Val|2.75|0.07|ul=m/s2}}<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/> \n| single_temperature       = {{Val|1,888|51|ul=K}}<ref name=EPE />\n<!-- ATMOSPHERE          --> \n<!-- NOTES               --> \n}}\n'''HAT-P-32b''' is a planet in the orbit of the [[Stellar classification#Class G|G-type]] or [[Stellar classification#Class F|F-type]] star [[HAT-P-32]], which is approximately 950 light years<ref name=\"Gaia\"/> away from Earth. HAT-P-32b was first recognized as a possible planet by the planet-searching [[HATNet Project]] in 2004, although difficulties in measuring its [[radial velocity]] prevented astronomers from verifying the planet until after three years of observation. The [[Blendanal]] program helped to rule out most of the alternatives that could explain what HAT-P-32b was, leading astronomers to determine that HAT-P-32b was most likely a planet. The discovery of HAT-P-32b and of [[HAT-P-33b]] was submitted to a journal on 6 June 2011.\n\nThe planet is considered a [[Hot Jupiter]], and although it is slightly less massive than Jupiter, it is bloated to nearly twice Jupiter's size. At the time of its discovery, HAT-P-32b had [[List of largest exoplanets|one of the largest radii known]] amongst extrasolar planets. This phenomenon, which has also been observed in planets like [[WASP-17b]] and [[HAT-P-33b]], has shown that something more than temperature is influencing why these planets become so large.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\n==Discovery==\nIt had been suggested that a planet was in the orbit of the star HAT-P-32 as early as 2004; these observations were collected by the six-telescope [[HATNet Project]], an organization in search of [[transit method|transiting]] planets, or planets that cross in front of their host stars as seen from Earth. However, attempts to confirm the planetary candidate were extremely difficult because of a high level of [[jitter]] (a random, shaky deviation in the measurements of HAT-P-32's [[radial velocity]]) present in the star's observations. High-level jitter prevented the most common technique, that of bisector analysis, from revealing the star's radial velocity with enough certainty to confirm the planet's existence.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nThe [[spectrum]] of HAT-P-32 was collected using the [[digital speedometer]] on Arizona's [[Fred Lawrence Whipple Observatory]] (FLWO). Analysis of the data found that HAT-P-32 was a single, moderately rotating [[dwarf star]]. Some of its parameters were also derived, including its [[effective temperature]] and [[surface gravity]].<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nBetween August 2007 and December 2010, twenty-eight spectra were collected using the [[High Resolution Echelle Spectrometer]] (HIRES) at the [[W.M. Keck Observatory]] in Hawaii. Twenty-five of these spectra were used to deduce HAT-P-32's radial velocity. To compensate for jitter, a greater number of spectra than that the usual for planetary candidates was collected. From this, it was concluded that stellar activity (and not the presence of yet-undiscovered planets) was the cause of the jitter.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nBecause astronomers concluded that the use of radial velocity could not, alone, establish the existence of planet HAT-P-32b, the [[KeplerCam CCD]] instrument on FLWO's 1.2m telescope was used to take [[photometry (astronomy)|photometric]] observations of HAT-P-32. The data collected using KeplerCam CCD helped astronomers constructed HAT-P-32's [[light curve]]. The light curve displayed a slight dimming at a point where HAT-P-32b was believed to transit its star.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nThe astronomers utilized [[Blendanal]], a program used to eliminate the possibilities of [[false positive]]s. This process serves a similar purpose to the [[Blender (technique)|Blender]] technique, which was used to verify some planets discovered by the [[Kepler (spacecraft)|Kepler]] spacecraft. In doing so, HAT-P-32's planet-like signature was found to not be caused by either a [[multiple star#Hierarchical systems|hierarchical triple star system]] or by a mixture of light between a bright single star and that of a [[binary star]] in the background. Although the possibility that HAT-P-32 is actually a binary star with a dim secondary companion nearly indistinguishable from the primary companion could not be ruled out, HAT-P-32b was confirmed as a planet based on the Blendanal analysis.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nBecause of the high jitter of the star, the best way to collect more data on HAT-P-32b would be to observe an [[occultation]] of HAT-P-32b behind its star using the [[Spitzer Space Telescope]].<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nHAT-P-32b's discovery was reported with that of HAT-P-33b in the ''[[Astrophysical Journal]]''.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\n==Host star==\nHAT-P-32, or GSC 3281\u201300800, is a double star; the primary is a [[Stellar classification#Class G|G-type]] or [[Stellar classification#Class F|F-type]] [[dwarf star]],<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/> and the secondary is a [[Stellar classification#Class M|M-type]] [[dwarf star]].<ref name=Zhao2014/> The system is located {{convert|292|pc|ly}} away from Earth.<ref name=\"Gaia\"/> With 1.176 [[solar mass]]es and 1.387 [[solar radius|solar radii]], HAT-P-32A is both larger and more massive than the Sun. HAT-P-32A's effective temperature is 6,001 [[Kelvin scale|K]], making it slightly hotter than the Sun, although it is younger, at an estimated age of 3.8 billion years, thus begun [[nuclear fusion]] in its core not long after the [[Archean]] eon started {{Val|4.031|0.003}}&nbsp;billion years ago.<ref name=EPE /> HAT-P-32A is metal-poor; its measured [[metallicity]] is [Fe/H] = -0.16, which means that it has 69% the iron content of the Sun.<ref name=EPE /> The star's surface gravity is determined to be 4.22, while its [[luminosity]] suggests that it emits 2.43 times the amount of energy that the Sun emits.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/> These parameters are adopted given the condition that the planet HAT-P-32b has an irregular ([[orbital eccentricity|eccentric]]) orbit.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nHAT-P-32 has an [[apparent magnitude]] of 11.197, which makes it invisible to the naked eye.<ref name=\"APASS DR9\"/> A search for a binary companion star using [[adaptive optics]] at the [[MMT Observatory]] discovered a companion at a distance of 2.9 [[Minute of arc|arcsecond]]s that is 3.4 magnitudes dimmer than the primary star.<ref name=\"Adams2013\"/>\n\nA very high level of jitter has been detected in the star's spectrum. There is a possibility that the jitter could be induced by the dimmer secondary companion. HAT-P-32's dimmer constituent probably has a mass that is under half of the Sun's mass,<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/> while it has a temperature of {{val|3,565|82}} [[Kelvin|K]].<ref name=Zhao2014/>\n\nOther planets with [[orbital period]]s that are smaller than that of HAT-P-32b's orbit may be present in this system. However, when the discovery of the planet was published, not enough radial velocity measurements had been collected to determine if this was the case.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\n==Characteristics==\n\nHAT-P-32b is a [[Hot Jupiter]] that has 0.941 [[Jupiter mass]]es and 2.037 [[Jupiter radius|Jupiter radii]]. In other words, HAT-P-32b is slightly less massive than Jupiter is, although it is nearly twice Jupiter's size.<ref name=EPE /> The planet's [[semimajor axis|average distance]] from its host star is 0.0344&nbsp;[[astronomical unit|AU]], or approximately 3% of the mean distance between the Earth and the Sun. It completes an orbit every 2.150009 days (51.6 hours).<ref name=EPE /> HAT-P-32b has an [[equilibrium temperature]] of 1888 K,<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/> which is fifteen times hotter than Jupiter's equilibrium temperature.<ref name=datatable />\n\nMany of the described characteristics are derived on the assumption that HAT-P-32b has an orbit that is elliptical (eccentric). The best fit for HAT-P-32b's orbital eccentricity is 0.163, denoting a slightly elliptical orbit, although the jitter effect observed in its host star has made the planet's eccentricity difficult to accurately find. The discoverers have also derived the planet's characteristics assuming that the planet has a circular orbit, although they have given preference to the elliptical model.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nBecause of HAT-P-32b's [[orbital inclination]] with respect to Earth is 88.7\u00ba, the planet is seen almost edge-on with respect to Earth.<ref name=EPE /> It has been found to transit its host star.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nHAT-P-32b had one of the highest radii known amongst planets at the time of its discovery. Like planets [[HAT-P-33b]] and [[WASP-17b]], which are similarly inflated, the mechanism behind this is unknown; it is not solely related to temperature, which is known to have an effect. This is especially clear when compared to [[WASP-18b]], a planet that is hotter than the aforementioned HAT and WASP planets, because despite its temperature its radius is far lower than that of its counterparts.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nIt was also found that the planet radius, observed with planetary transits, varies with wavelength. Different radii for each wavelength could arise from an atmosphere where a Rayleigh scattering haze is combined with a grey cloud deck.<ref name=Tregloan-Reed2018/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Adams2013\">{{cite journal | title=Adaptive Optics Images. II. 12 Kepler Objects of Interest and 15 Confirmed Transiting Planets | last1=Adams | first1=E. R. | last2=Dupree | first2=A. K. | last3=Kulesa | first3=C. | last4=McCarthy | first4=D. | display-authors=1 | journal=The Astronomical Journal | volume=146 | issue=1 | at=9  | year=2013 | arxiv=1305.6548 | bibcode=2013AJ....146....9A | doi=10.1088/0004-6256/146/1/9 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"APASS DR9\">{{cite journal | title=VizieR Online Data Catalog: AAVSO Photometric All Sky Survey (APASS) DR9 (Henden+, 2016) | last1=Henden | first1=A. A. | last2=Templeton | first2=M. | last3=Terrell | first3=D. | last4=Smith | first4=T. C. | last5=Levine | first5=S. | last6=Welch | first6=D. | display-authors=1 | journal=VizieR On-line Data Catalog: II/336. Originally Published in: 2015AAS...22533616H | volume=2336 | year=2016 | bibcode=2016yCat.2336....0H }}[http://webviz.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/VizieR-5?-out.add=.&-source=II/336/apass9&recno=2458322 Vizier catalog entry ]</ref>\n\n<ref name=datatable>{{cite web |url=http://www.kepler.nasa.gov/Mission/discoveries/ |title=Kepler Discoveries |author= |date=2011 |work=[[Ames Research Center]] |publisher=[[NASA]] |accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=EPE>{{cite web |url=http://exoplanet.eu/catalog/hat-p-32_b/ |title=Planet HAT-P-32b |author=Jean Schneider |date=2011 |website= |publisher=[[Extrasolar Planets Encyclopaedia]] |accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gaia\">{{cite DR2|356348286886230272}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Hartman2011\">{{cite journal | title=HAT-P-32b and HAT-P-33b: Two Highly Inflated Hot Jupiters Transiting High-jitter Stars | last1=Hartman | first1=J. D. | last2=Bakos | first2=G. \u00c1. | last3=Torres | first3=G. | last4=Latham | first4=D. W. | last5=Kov\u00e1cs | first5=G\u00e9za | last6=B\u00e9ky | first6=B. | last7=Quinn | first7=S. N. | last8=Mazeh | first8=T. | last9=Shporer | first9=A. | last10=Marcy | first10=G. W. | last11=Howard | first11=A. W. | last12=Fischer | first12=D. A. | last13=Johnson | first13=J. A. | last14=Esquerdo | first14=G. A. | last15=Noyes | first15=R. W. | last16=Sasselov | first16=D. D. | last17=Stefanik | first17=R. P. | last18=Fernandez | first18=J. M. | last19=Szklen\u00e1r | first19=T. | last20=L\u00e1z\u00e1r | first20=J. | last21=Papp | first21=I. | last22=S\u00e1ri | first22=P. | display-authors=1 | journal=The Astrophysical Journal | volume=742 | issue=1 | at=59 | year=2011 | arxiv=1106.1212 | bibcode=2011ApJ...742...59H | doi=10.1088/0004-637X/742/1/59 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Sada2012\">{{cite journal | title=Extrasolar Planet Transits Observed at Kitt Peak National Observatory | last1=Sada | first1=Pedro V. | last2=Deming | first2=Drake | last3=Jennings | first3=Donald E. | last4=Jackson | first4=Brian K. | last5=Hamilton | first5=Catrina M. | last6=Fraine | first6=Jonathan | last7=Peterson | first7=Steven W. | last8=Haase | first8=Flynn | last9=Bays | first9=Kevin | last10=Lunsford | first10=Allen | last11=O'Gorman | first11=Eamon | display-authors=1 | journal=Publications of the Astronomical Society of the Pacific | volume=124 | issue=913 | pages=212\u2013229 | year=2012 | arxiv=1202.2799 | bibcode=2012PASP..124..212S | doi=10.1086/665043}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Zhao2014>{{cite journal|bibcode=2014ApJ...796..115Z|title=Characterization of the Atmosphere of the Hot Jupiter HAT-P-32Ab and the M-dwarf Companion HAT-P-32B|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=796|issue=2|pages=115|last1=Zhao|first1=Ming|last2=O'Rourke|first2=Joseph G.|last3=Wright|first3=Jason T.|last4=Knutson|first4=Heather A.|last5=Burrows|first5=Adam|last6=Fortney|first6=Johnathan|last7=Ngo|first7=Henry|last8=Fulton|first8=Benjamin J.|last9=Baranec|first9=Christoph|last10=Riddle|first10=Reed|last11=Law|first11=Nicholas M.|last12=Muirhead|first12=Philip S.|last13=Hinkley|first13=Sasha|last14=Showman|first14=Adam P.|last15=Curtis|first15=Jason|last16=Burruss|first16=Rick|year=2014|doi=10.1088/0004-637X/796/2/115|arxiv=1410.0968}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Tregloan-Reed2018>{{cite journal|bibcode=2018MNRAS.474.5485T|title=Possible detection of a bimodal cloud distribution in the atmosphere of HAT-P-32 a b from multiband photometry|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume=474|issue=4|pages=5485|last1=Tregloan-Reed|first1=J.|last2=Southworth|first2=J.|last3=Mancini|first3=L.|last4=Molli\u00e8re|first4=P.|last5=Ciceri|first5=S.|last6=Bruni|first6=I.|last7=Ricci|first7=D.|last8=Ayala-Loera|first8=C.|last9=Henning|first9=T.|year=2018|doi=10.1093/mnras/stx3147|arxiv=1712.00415}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Andromeda (constellation)}}\n\n[[Category:Andromeda (constellation)]]\n[[Category:Exoplanets discovered in 2011]]\n[[Category:Transiting exoplanets]]\n[[Category:Hot Jupiters]]\n[[Category:Giant planets]]\n[[Category:Exoplanets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox planet\n| name                     = HAT-P-32b\n<!-- DISCOVERY           -->\n| discoverer               = Hartman ''et al.''<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n| discovery_site           = [[HATNet]] ([[Fred Lawrence Whipple Observatory|FLWO]])/[[W.M. Keck Observatory|Keck]]<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n| discovered               = Published November 3, 2011<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n| discovery_method         = [[Transit method]]<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n<!-- ORBITAL             --> \n| epoch                    = J2000\n| apsis                    = astron\n| semimajor                = 0.0343 \u00b1 0.0004<ref name=EPE /> [[astronomical unit|AU]]\n| eccentricity             = 0.0072 {{\u00b1|0.07|0.0064}}<ref name=EPE />\n| period                   = 2.1500103 \u00b1 0.0000003<ref name=\"Sada2012\"/> [[day|d]]\n| inclination              = 88.9 \u00b1 0.4 [[degree (angle)|\u00b0]]<ref name=EPE />\n| arg_peri                 = 96 {{\u00b1|180|11}}<ref name=EPE />\n| star                     = [[HAT-P-32]] (GSC 3281-00800)\n<!-- PHYS CHARS          --> \n| mean_radius              = 1.789 \u00b1 0.025<ref name=EPE /> {{Jupiter radius|link=y}}\n| mass                     = 0.86 \u00b1 0.164<ref name=EPE /> {{Jupiter mass|link=y}}\n| surface_grav             = 2.75 \u00b1 0.07<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/> [[Metre per second squared|m/s\u00b2]] \n| single_temperature       = 1,888 \u00b1 51<ref name=EPE /> [[K]]\n<!-- ATMOSPHERE          --> \n<!-- NOTES               --> \n}}\n'''HAT-P-32b''' is a planet in the orbit of the [[Stellar classification#Class G|G-type]] or [[Stellar classification#Class F|F-type]] star [[HAT-P-32]], which is approximately 950 light years<ref name=\"Gaia\"/> away from Earth. HAT-P-32b was first recognized as a possible planet by the planet-searching [[HATNet Project]] in 2004, although difficulties in measuring its [[radial velocity]] prevented astronomers from verifying the planet until after three years of observation. The [[Blendanal]] program helped to rule out most of the alternatives that could explain what HAT-P-32b was, leading astronomers to determine that HAT-P-32b was most likely a planet. The discovery of HAT-P-32b and of [[HAT-P-33b]] was submitted to a journal on June 6, 2011.\n\nThe planet is considered a [[Hot Jupiter]], and although it is slightly less massive than Jupiter, it is bloated to nearly twice Jupiter's size. At the time of its discovery, HAT-P-32b had [[List of largest exoplanets|one of the largest radii known]] amongst extrasolar planets. This phenomenon, which has also been observed in planets like [[WASP-17b]] and [[HAT-P-33b]], has shown that something more than temperature is influencing why these planets become so large.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\n==Discovery==\nIt had been suggested that a planet was in the orbit of the star HAT-P-32 as early as 2004; these observations were collected by the six-telescope [[HATNet Project]], an organization in search of [[transit method|transiting]] planets, or planets that cross in front of their host stars as seen from Earth. However, attempts to confirm the planetary candidate were extremely difficult because of a high level of [[jitter]] (a random, shaky deviation in the measurements of HAT-P-32's [[radial velocity]]) present in the star's observations. High-level jitter prevented the most common technique, that of bisector analysis, from revealing the star's radial velocity with enough certainty to confirm the planet's existence.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nThe [[spectrum]] of HAT-P-32 was collected using the [[digital speedometer]] on Arizona's [[Fred Lawrence Whipple Observatory]] (FLWO). Analysis of the data found that HAT-P-32 was a single, moderately rotating [[dwarf star]]. Some of its parameters were also derived, including its [[effective temperature]] and [[surface gravity]].<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nBetween August 2007 and December 2010, twenty-eight spectra were collected using the [[High Resolution Echelle Spectrometer]] (HIRES) at the [[W.M. Keck Observatory]] in Hawaii. Twenty-five of these spectra were used to deduce HAT-P-32's radial velocity. To compensate for jitter, a greater number of spectra than that the usual for planetary candidates was collected. From this, it was concluded that stellar activity (and not the presence of yet-undiscovered planets) was the cause of the jitter.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nBecause astronomers concluded that the use of radial velocity could not, alone, establish the existence of planet HAT-P-32b, the [[KeplerCam CCD]] instrument on FLWO's 1.2m telescope was used to take [[photometry (astronomy)|photometric]] observations of HAT-P-32. The data collected using KeplerCam CCD helped astronomers constructed HAT-P-32's [[light curve]]. The light curve displayed a slight dimming at a point where HAT-P-32b was believed to transit its star.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nThe astronomers utilized [[Blendanal]], a program used to eliminate the possibilities of [[false positive]]s. This process serves a similar purpose to the [[Blender (technique)|Blender]] technique, which was used to verify some planets discovered by the [[Kepler (spacecraft)|Kepler]] spacecraft. In doing so, HAT-P-32's planet-like signature was found to not be caused by either a [[multiple star#Hierarchical systems|hierarchical triple star system]] or by a mixture of light between a bright single star and that of a [[binary star]] in the background. Although the possibility that HAT-P-32 is actually a binary star with a dim secondary companion nearly indistinguishable from the primary companion could not be ruled out, HAT-P-32b was confirmed as a planet based on the Blendanal analysis.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nBecause of the high jitter of the star, the best way to collect more data on HAT-P-32b would be to observe an [[occultation]] of HAT-P-32b behind its star using the [[Spitzer Space Telescope]].<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nHAT-P-32b's discovery was reported with that of HAT-P-33b in the ''[[Astrophysical Journal]]''.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\n==Host star==\nHAT-P-32, or GSC 3281\u201300800, is a double star; the primary is a [[Stellar classification#Class G|G-type]] or [[Stellar classification#Class F|F-type]] [[dwarf star]],<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/> and the secondary is a [[Stellar classification#Class M|M-type]] [[dwarf star]].<ref name=Zhao2014/> The system is located {{convert|292|pc|ly}} away from Earth.<ref name=\"Gaia\"/> With 1.176 [[solar mass]]es and 1.387 [[solar radius|solar radii]], HAT-P-32A is both larger and more massive than the Sun. HAT-P-32A's effective temperature is 6,001 [[Kelvin scale|K]], making it slightly hotter than the Sun, although it is younger, at an estimated age of 3.8 billion years, thus begun [[nuclear fusion]] in its core not long after the [[Archean]] eon started 4.031 \u00b1 0.003 billion years ago.<ref name=EPE /> HAT-P-32A is metal-poor; its measured [[metallicity]] is [Fe/H] = -0.16, which means that it has 69% the iron content of the Sun.<ref name=EPE /> The star's surface gravity is determined to be 4.22, while its [[luminosity]] suggests that it emits 2.43 times the amount of energy that the Sun emits.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/> These parameters are adopted given the condition that the planet HAT-P-32b has an irregular ([[orbital eccentricity|eccentric]]) orbit.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nHAT-P-32 has an [[apparent magnitude]] of 11.197, which makes it invisible to the naked eye.<ref name=\"APASS DR9\"/> A search for a binary companion star using [[adaptive optics]] at the [[MMT Observatory]] discovered a companion at a distance of 2.9 [[Minute of arc|arcsecond]]s that is 3.4 magnitudes dimmer than the primary star.<ref name=\"Adams2013\"/>\n\nA very high level of jitter has been detected in the star's spectrum. There is a possibility that the jitter could be induced by the dimmer secondary companion. HAT-P-32's dimmer constituent probably has a mass that is under half of the Sun's mass,<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/> while it has a temperature of {{val|3,565|82}} [[Kelvin|K]].<ref name=Zhao2014/>\n\nOther planets with [[orbital period]]s that are smaller than that of HAT-P-32b's orbit may be present in this system. However, when the discovery of the planet was published, not enough radial velocity measurements had been collected to determine if this was the case.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\n==Characteristics==\n\nHAT-P-32b is a [[Hot Jupiter]] that has 0.941 [[Jupiter mass]]es and 2.037 [[Jupiter radius|Jupiter radii]]. In other words, HAT-P-32b is slightly less massive than Jupiter is, although it is nearly twice Jupiter's size.<ref name=EPE /> The planet's [[semimajor axis|average distance]] from its host star is 0.0344 [[astronomical unit|AU]], or approximately 3% of the mean distance between the Earth and the Sun. It completes an orbit every 2.150009 days (51.6 hours).<ref name=EPE /> HAT-P-32b has an [[equilibrium temperature]] of 1888 K,<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/> which is fifteen times hotter than Jupiter's equilibrium temperature.<ref name=datatable />\n\nMany of the described characteristics are derived on the assumption that HAT-P-32b has an orbit that is elliptical (eccentric). The best fit for HAT-P-32b's orbital eccentricity is 0.163, denoting a slightly elliptical orbit, although the jitter effect observed in its host star has made the planet's eccentricity difficult to accurately find. The discoverers have also derived the planet's characteristics assuming that the planet has a circular orbit, although they have given preference to the elliptical model.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nBecause of HAT-P-32b's [[orbital inclination]] with respect to Earth is 88.7\u00ba, the planet is seen almost edge-on with respect to Earth.<ref name=EPE /> It has been found to transit its host star.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nHAT-P-32b had one of the highest radii known amongst planets at the time of its discovery. Like planets [[HAT-P-33b]] and [[WASP-17b]], which are similarly inflated, the mechanism behind this is unknown; it is not solely related to temperature, which is known to have an effect. This is especially clear when compared to [[WASP-18b]], a planet that is hotter than the aforementioned HAT and WASP planets, because despite its temperature its radius is far lower than that of its counterparts.<ref name=\"Hartman2011\"/>\n\nIt was also found that the planet radius, observed with planetary transits, varies with wavelength. Different radii for each wavelength could arise from an atmosphere where a Rayleigh scattering haze is combined with a grey cloud deck.<ref name=Tregloan-Reed2018/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Adams2013\">{{cite journal | title=Adaptive Optics Images. II. 12 Kepler Objects of Interest and 15 Confirmed Transiting Planets | last1=Adams | first1=E. R. | last2=Dupree | first2=A. K. | last3=Kulesa | first3=C. | last4=McCarthy | first4=D. | display-authors=1 | journal=The Astronomical Journal | volume=146 | issue=1 | at=9  | year=2013 | arxiv=1305.6548 | bibcode=2013AJ....146....9A | doi=10.1088/0004-6256/146/1/9 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"APASS DR9\">{{cite journal | title=VizieR Online Data Catalog: AAVSO Photometric All Sky Survey (APASS) DR9 (Henden+, 2016) | last1=Henden | first1=A. A. | last2=Templeton | first2=M. | last3=Terrell | first3=D. | last4=Smith | first4=T. C. | last5=Levine | first5=S. | last6=Welch | first6=D. | display-authors=1 | journal=VizieR On-line Data Catalog: II/336. Originally Published in: 2015AAS...22533616H | volume=2336 | year=2016 | bibcode=2016yCat.2336....0H }}[http://webviz.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/VizieR-5?-out.add=.&-source=II/336/apass9&recno=2458322 Vizier catalog entry ]</ref>\n\n<ref name=datatable>{{cite web |url=http://www.kepler.nasa.gov/Mission/discoveries/  |title=Kepler Discoveries |author= |date=2011 |work=[[Ames Research Center]] |publisher=[[NASA]] |accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=EPE>{{cite web |url=http://exoplanet.eu/catalog/hat-p-32_b/ |title=Planet HAT-P-32b |author=Jean Schneider |date=2011 |website= |publisher=[[Extrasolar Planets Encyclopaedia]] |accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gaia\">{{cite DR2|356348286886230272}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Hartman2011\">{{cite journal | title=HAT-P-32b and HAT-P-33b: Two Highly Inflated Hot Jupiters Transitin